Anyone who knows much about my family knows that women run the show. The Clark sisters were both loving and fierce, and like my grandmom, they were not to be crossed by mere mortals. That strength was as evident as ever over the last month as my 89 year old Aunt Carolyn stood watch over my mother‚Äôs last days on this earth. Her steadfastness and strength were a remarkable thing to behold. ‚ÄúI saw my baby sister‚Äôs first breath and I will be here to see her last. I owe her that.‚Äù

Mom and Dad met in Lexington at the University of Kentucky, got married in Rome, Georgia in 1955 and moved to Georgetown, Kentucky where Dad finished school while Mom taught high school and was church organist at the Georgetown Episcopalian Church. They had no car, little money and walked everywhere they went. It was a magical time for them.

I was the youngest in our family and grew up scared of everything. Mom brought to me blessed assurance every day and let me know that I was capable of doing anything that I wanted. Her faith in God set my footsteps on firm ground and her unending confidence in my abilities eventually turned my fears into fearlessness. I loved my dad so much but owe so much of who I am to my mom. She passed away peacefully this weekend after suffering from dementia for 7 years. Mom prayed for years that she could once again be ‚Äúwith George and Mama‚Äù. This weekend, God finally answered her prayers.
